These relationships were used to make the normaliztion practical by making it come under the 1NF,2NF,3NF.

# First Normal Form (1NF)
A table is in First Normal Form when:
- all values are atomic(no repeating groups)
- every record is uniquely identifiable

## Implementation

The schema satisfies 1NF because:
- each column stores only one value
- tables contain unique "primary keys"
- repeating groups were removed

## Example

| submission_id | languages |
|----------------|-----------|
| 1 | Python, Java |

the design stores only one language per submission:

| submission_id | programming_language |
|----------------|----------------------|
| 1 | Python |

This improves query performance and consistency.

---
# Second Normal Form (2NF)
A table is in Second Normal Form when:
- it is already in 1NF
- non-key attributes fully depend on the entire primary key

## Example 1: Enrollments Table
The enrollments table stores:
- enrollment_id
- student_id
- course_id
- enrollment_status

Course details such as course_name and credits are stored separately in the courses table.

### Before Separation

| enrollment_id | student_id | course_name | credits |
|----------------|------------|-------------|----------|

This causes repeated course information.

### After Separation
Enrollments table:
- enrollment_id
- student_id
- course_id
Courses table:
- course_id
- course_name
- credits
This removes partial dependency and reduces redundancy.

## Example 2: Contest Problems

Contest information and problem information are separated into different tables.
The many-to-many relationship is resolved using:
- contest_problems table
This prevents repeated contest and problem details.

# Third Normal Form (3NF)

A table is in Third Normal Form when:
- it is already in 2NF
- non-key attributes do not depend on other non-key attributes

## Example 1: Batch Information

Student records contain only:
- batch_id

Actual batch details are stored in the batches table.

### Benefits
- avoids repeated batch information
- simplifies updates
- improves consistency

---

## Example 2: Test Results

Submission evaluation results are separated into the test_results table instead of storing all testcase outputs inside submissions.

This prevents unnecessary repetition and improves scalability.

---

# Examples of Repeated or Redundant Data

## Example 1
Course details would repeat in enrollments if course_name and credits were stored directly inside the enrollments table.

Normalization solved this by creating a separate courses table.

---

## Example 2
Problem details could repeat in contest records if problems were stored directly inside contests.

Normalization solved this using the contest_problems mapping table.

---

## Example 3
Student information would repeat in submissions if student names and emails were stored repeatedly for every submission.

Normalization solved this by referencing students using student_id.

---

# Examples Where Separating Data Improved Design

## Example 1: Courses Table

Separating course information into a dedicated courses table:
- reduced duplicate data
- simplified updates
- improved consistency

---

## Example 2: Test Cases Table

Separating test case information from problems:
- improved modularity
- supported multiple test cases per problem
- reduced repeated input/output storage

---

# Functional Dependency Examples

## Example 1

student_id → full_name, email, batch_id

Meaning:
A student_id uniquely determines student details.

---

## Example 2

problem_id → title, difficulty, max_score

Meaning:
A problem_id uniquely determines problem information.

---

# Partial Dependency Example

In the enrollments relationship:

(student_id, course_id) → enrollment_status

The enrollment status depends on the combination of both student and course.

This relationship is handled properly using the enrollments table.

---

# Design Trade-offs

Some design decisions were intentionally simplified.

## Example 1
Status fields such as:
- enrollment_status
- attendance_status
- submission_status

were stored as text values instead of separate lookup tables.

This simplifies implementation while still maintaining clarity.

---

## Example 2
The raw_student_import table remains partially denormalized because it acts as a temporary staging table during import operations.

This improves import flexibility.

---

# Final Normalization Status

The final database schema approximately satisfies:

- First Normal Form (1NF)
- Second Normal Form (2NF)
- Third Normal Form (3NF)

The design:
- reduces redundancy
- improves data consistency
- supports relational integrity
- minimizes update anomalies
- improves maintainability

while still keeping the schema practical and easy to manage.
